{"title_page": "High-speed camera", "text_new": "{{see also|High-speed photography#High-speed film cameras}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\nA '''high-speed camera''' is a device capable of capturing moving images with exposures of less than 1/1,000 second or frame rates in excess of 250 frames per second.<ref>Journal of the Society of Motion Picture Engineers: High-Speed Photography, Preface p.5, Mar 1949</ref> It is used for recording fast-moving objects as photographic images onto a storage medium.  After recording, the images stored on the medium can be played back in [[slow motion]]. Early high-speed cameras used film to record the high-speed events, but were superseded by entirely electronic devices using either a [[charge-coupled device]] (CCD) or a [[CMOS]] [[active pixel sensor]], recording, typically, over 1,000 frames per second onto [[DRAM]], to be played back slowly to study the motion for scientific study of transient phenomena.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/HSV%20White%20Paper.pdf |title=High Frame Rate Electronic Imaging |access-date=2010-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000301/http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/HSV%20White%20Paper.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nA high-speed camera can be classified as:\n# A high-speed film camera which records to film,\n# A high-speed video camera which records to electronic memory,\n# A high-speed framing camera which records images on multiple image planes or multiple locations on the same image plane<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aimed-research.com/help.html | title=High-Speed Camera Tutorials}}</ref> (generally film or a network of CCD cameras),\n# A high-speed streak camera which records a series of line-sized images to film or electronic memory.\n\nA normal [[Film|motion picture]] film is played back at 24 [[frames per second]], while television uses 25 frames/s ([[PAL]]) or 29.97 frames/s ([[NTSC]]). High-speed film cameras can film up to a quarter of a million frames per second by running the film over a rotating [[prism (optics)|prism]] or [[mirror]] instead of using a [[shutter (photography)|shutter]], thus reducing the need for stopping and starting the film behind a shutter which would tear the film stock at such speeds. Using this technique one second of action can be stretched to more than ten minutes of playback time (super slow motion). High-speed video cameras are widely used for scientific research,<ref>scientific research {{Cite journal|last= Chen|first= Xianfeng |title= Effect of CH4\u2013Air Ratios on Gas Explosion Flame Microstructurec and Propagation Behaviors |journal= Energies |volume= 5 |issue= 10 |pages= 4132\u20134146 |doi= 10.3390/en5104132 |year= 2012 }}</ref><ref>scientific research{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first= Christopher V. |title= Ballistic tongue projection in chameleons maintains high performance at low temperature|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/107/12/5495.full.pdf|accessdate=2 February 2010|doi=10.1073/pnas.0910778107|volume=107|year=2010|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|pages=5495\u20135499 }}</ref>  military test and evaluation,<ref>{{cite web|last=Chu|first= Dr. Peter C.|title= Non-Cylindrical Mine Drop Experiment |url= http://faculty.nps.edu/pcchu/web_paper/proceedings/jcot/midex2.pdf |date=4 May 2006|publisher= Seventh International Symposium on Technology and Mine Problem, NPS, Monterey, California, USA }}</ref> and industry.<ref>{{cite web|title= Photron Camera Honored by Japan Society of Mechanical Engineers |url= http://www.qualitymag.com/Articles/Industry_Headlines/BNP_GUID_9-5-2006_A_10000000000000241598|accessdate=January 23, 2008 |publisher=Quality Magazine}}</ref>  Examples of industrial applications are filming a manufacturing line to better tune the machine, or in the car industry filming a [[crash test]] to investigate the effect on the [[crash dummy]] passengers and the [[automobile]]. Today, the digital high-speed camera has replaced the film camera used for Vehicle Impact Testing.<ref>[http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/Kodak%20RO_SPIE.pdf Replacing 16&nbsp;mm Film Cameras with High Definition Digital Cameras]</ref> \n[[File:Schlieren Video Of Shotshell Transitional Intermediate Ballistics - Nathan Boor of Aimed Research.ogv|thumb|[[Schlieren]] video of an intermediate ballistic event of a shotshell cartridge. Nathan Boor, Aimed Research.]]\n[[Television series]] such as ''[[MythBusters]]'' and ''[[Time Warp (TV series)|Time Warp]]'' often use high-speed cameras to show their tests in slow motion. Saving the recorded high-speed images can be time consuming because {{As of|2017|lc=on}}, consumer cameras have resolutions up to four megapixels with frame rates of over 1,000 per second which will record at a rate of 11 gigabytes per second. Technologically these cameras are very advanced, yet saving images requires use of slower standard video-computer interfaces.<ref>[http://www.definitionmagazine.com/journal/2011/1/4/review-high-speed-cameras.html REVIEW: High Speed Cameras, Jan. 4, 2011]</ref> While recording is very fast, saving images is considerably slower.\nTo reduce the storage space required and the time required for people to examine a recording, only the parts of an action which are of interest or relevance can be selected to film. When recording a cyclical process for industrial breakdown analysis, only the relevant part of each cycle is filmed.\n\nA problem for high-speed cameras is the needed [[exposure (photography)|exposure]] for the film; very bright light is needed to be able to film at 40,000&nbsp;fps, sometimes leading to the subject of examination being destroyed because of the heat of the lighting.\nMonochromatic (black and white) filming is sometimes used to reduce the light intensity required.\nEven higher speed imaging is possible using specialized electronic [[charge-coupled device]] (CCD) imaging systems, which can achieve speeds of over 25&nbsp;million fps. These cameras, however, still use rotating mirrors, like their older film counterparts. Solid state cameras can achieve speeds of up to 10 million fps. <ref>https://www.shimadzu.com/an/test/hpv/hpv-x2/index.html</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228937545_Brandaris_128_A_digital_25_million_frames_per_second_camera_with_128_highly_sensitive_frames Brandaris 128: A digital 25 million frames per second camera with 128 highly sensitive frames]</ref> All development in high-speed cameras is now focused on digital video cameras which have many operational and cost benefits over film cameras.\n\nIn 2010 researchers built a camera exposing each frame for two trillionths of a second ([[Second#Multiples and submultiples|picoseconds]]), for an effective frame rate of half a trillion fps ([[femto-photography]]).<ref name=raskarspageatmit>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://web.media.mit.edu/~raskar/trillionfps/ |title=Visualizing Light at Trillion FPS, Camera Culture, MIT Media Lab |pages=1 |doi=10.1145/2037715.2037730 |publisher=Web.media.mit.edu |date=2011-12-13 |accessdate=2012-10-04|chapter=Slow art with a trillion frames per second camera |last1=Velten |first1=Andreas |last2=Lawson |first2=Everett |last3=Bardagjy |first3=Andrew |last4=Bawendi |first4=Moungi |last5=Raskar |first5=Ramesh |isbn=9781450309714 }} Work supported by research grants in 2009 and 2010.</ref><ref name=Velten>{{cite journal|last=Velten|first=Andreas|author2=Di Wu |author3=Adrian Jarabo |author4=Belen Masia |author5=Christopher Barsi |author6=Chinmaya Joshi |author7=Everett Lawson |author8=Moungi Bawendi |author9=Diego Gutierrez |author10=Ramesh Raskar |title=Femto-Photography: Capturing and Visualizing the Propagation of Light|journal=ACM Transactions on Graphics|date=July 2013|volume=32|issue=4|url=http://giga.cps.unizar.es/~diegog/ficheros/pdf_papers/femto.pdf|accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> Modern high-speed cameras operate by converting the incident light ([[photons]]) into a stream of [[electrons]] which are then deflected onto a [[photoanode]], back into photons, which can then be recorded onto either film or CCD.\n\n==Uses in television==\n*The show ''[[MythBusters]]'' prominently uses high-speed cameras for measuring speed or height.\n*''[[Time Warp (TV series)|Time Warp]]'' was centered around the use of high-speed cameras to slow things down that are usually too fast to see with the naked eye.\n*High-speed cameras are frequently used in [[television production]]s of many major sporting events for [[slow motion]] [[instant replay]]s when normal slow motion is not slow enough, such as international [[Cricket]] matches.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nacinc.com/did-you-know/nac-cameras-are-popular-choices-for-european-broadcasting/| title=NAC High Speed Cameras Are Popular Choices for European Broadcasting| accessdate = 8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Uses in science==\nHigh-speed cameras are frequently used in science in order to characterize events which happen too fast for traditional film speeds. [[Biomechanics]] employs such cameras to capture high-speed animal movements, such as [[jumping]] by frogs and insects,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kesel |first= Antonia B.|title= Quantifying the Landing Reaction of Cockroaches |url= http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/doc/ARI/ARI%20Study%20Report/ACT-RPT-BIO-ARI-08-6302-CockroachLanding-Bremen.pdf |accessdate=15 December 2009|journal=University of Applied Sciences Bremen}}</ref> [[Aquatic predation#Suction feeding|suction feeding]] in fish, the strikes of [[mantis shrimp]], and the aerodynamic study of pigeons' helicopter-like movements <ref>{{cite journal | last=Ros | first=Ivo G. | last2=Bassman | first2=Lori C. | last3=Badger | first3=Marc A. | last4=Pierson | first4=Alyssa N. | last5=Biewener | first5=Andrew A. | title=Pigeons steer like helicopters and generate down- and upstroke lift during low speed turns | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume=108 | issue=50 | date=2011-12-13 | issn=0027-8424 | pmid=22123982 | pmc=3250151 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1107519108 | pages=19990\u201319995 | bibcode=2011PNAS..10819990R }}</ref> using [[motion analysis]] of the resulting sequences from one or more cameras to characterize the motion in either 2-D or 3-D.\n\nThe move from film to digital technology has greatly reduced the difficulty in use of these technologies with unpredictable behaviors, specifically via the use of continuous recording and post-triggering. With film high-speed cameras, an investigator must start the film then attempt to entice the animal to perform the behavior in the short time before the film runs out, resulting in many useless sequences where the animal behaves too late or not at all. In modern digital high-speed cameras,<ref>{{Cite book|last= Balch|first= Kris S.| title= Fourth-generation motion analyzer |url=http://proceedings.spiedigitallibrary.org/proceeding.aspx?articleid=950818 |date=16 September 1990|journal=Proc. SPIE 1358, 19th Intl Congress on High-Speed Photography and Photonics|volume= 1358|pages= 373\u2013398|doi= 10.1117/12.23937|isbn= 9780819404190}}</ref> the camera can simply record continuously as the investigator attempts to elicit the behavior, following which a trigger button will stop the recording and allow the investigator to save a given time interval before and after the trigger (determined by frame rate, image size and memory capacity during continuous recording). Most software allows saving a subset of recorded frames, minimizing file size issues by eliminating useless frames before or after the sequence of interest. Such triggering can also be used to synchronize recording across multiple cameras.\n\nThe explosion of alkali metals on contact with water has been studied using a high-speed camera. Frame-by-frame analysis of a sodium/potassium alloy exploding in water, combined with molecular dynamic simulations, suggested that the initial expansion may be the result of a [[Coulomb explosion]] and not combustion of hydrogen gas as previously thought.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mason|first=Philip E.|last2=Uhlig|first2=Frank|last3=Van\u011bk|first3=V\u00e1clav|last4=Buttersack|first4=Tillmann|last5=Bauerecker|first5=Sigurd|last6=Jungwirth|first6=Pavel|date=2015-03-01|title=Coulomb explosion during the early stages of the reaction of alkali metals with water|journal=Nature Chemistry|language=en|volume=7|issue=3|pages=250\u2013254|doi=10.1038/nchem.2161|pmid=25698335|issn=1755-4330|bibcode=2015NatCh...7..250M}}</ref>\n\nDigital high-speed camera footage has strongly contributed to the understanding of [[lightning]] when combined with [[electric field]] measuring instrumentation and sensors which can map the propagation of lightning leaders through the detection of [[radio waves]] generated by this process.<ref name=ztresearch>{{cite web |url=https://ztresearch.blog/education/ |website=ZT Research |access-date=8 September 2018|title=Education |date=2017-05-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses in industry==\nWhen moving from reactive maintenance to [[predictive maintenance]], it is crucial that breakdowns are really understood. One of the basic analysis techniques is to use high-speed cameras in order to characterize events which happen too fast to see, e.g. during production. Similar to use in science, with a pre- or post-triggering capability the camera can simply record continuously as the mechanic waits for the breakdown to happen, following which a trigger signal (internal or external) will stop the recording and allow the investigator to save a given time interval prior to the trigger (determined by frame rate, image size, and memory capacity during continuous recording). Some software allows viewing the issues in real time, by displaying only a subset of recorded frames, minimizing file size and watch time issues by eliminating useless frames before or after the sequence of interest.\n\nHigh-speed video cameras are used to augment other industrial technologies such as x-ray radiography.  When used with the proper phosphor screen which converts x-rays into visible light, high-speed cameras can be used to capture high-speed x-ray videos of events inside mechanical devices and biological specimens. The imaging speed is mainly limited by the phosphor screen decay rate and intensity gain which has a direct relationship on the camera's exposure. Pulsed x-ray sources limit frame rate and should be properly synchronized with camera frame captures.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aimed-research.com/Services.html | title=High-Speed Imaging Services - Aimed Research}}</ref>\n\n==Uses in warfare==\nIn 1950 [[Morton Sultanoff]], an engineer for the U.S.&nbsp;Army at Aberdeen Proving ground, invented a super high-speed camera that took frames at one-millionth of a second, and was fast enough to record the shock wave of a small explosion.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ydgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA158&dq=1954+Popular+Mechanics+January&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WSfYT4GmKcOA2wW3ycWOCw&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBzgy#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Super Speed Camera Films Shock Wave\"] ''Popular Mechanics'', October 1950, p. 158.</ref> High Speed digital cameras have been used to study how mines dropped from the air will deploy in near-shore regions,<ref>weapon development{{cite web |last= Chu |first= Dr. Peter C. |title= Non-Cylindrical Mine Drop Experiment |url= http://faculty.nps.edu/pcchu/web_paper/proceedings/jcot/midex2.pdf |accessdate= 4 May 2006 |publisher= Seventh International Symposium on Technology and Mine Problem, NPS, Monterey, California, USA }}.  By using high speed digital cameras to record and playback the images in slow motion, the trajectory of a mine entering into the water can be optimized for accuracy by adjusting the shape of the mine and the entry angle into the water.  There are many instances of high speed digital cameras used to study firearm ballistics{{cite web|title=Handgun Wounding Effects Due to Bullet Rotational Velocity|url=http://www.brassfetcher.com/Wounding%20Theory/Handgun%20Wounding%20Effects%20due%20to%20Rotational%20Velocity.pdf|accessdate=18 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222013624/http://www.brassfetcher.com/Wounding%20Theory/Handgun%20Wounding%20Effects%20due%20to%20Rotational%20Velocity.pdf|archive-date=22 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> including development of various weapon systems.  In 2005 high speed digital cameras with 4 megapixel resolution, recording at 1500 fps, were replacing the 35mm and 70mm high speed film cameras used on tracking mounts on test ranges that capture ballistic intercepts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bridges |first= Andrew |title= INDUSTRY VIEW: Military test ranges make the switch from film to digital imaging |url=http://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/print/volume-16/issue-8/departments/electro-optics-watch/industry-view-military-test-ranges-make-the-switch-from-film-to-digital-imaging.html|date=1 August 2005|accessdate= 1 August 2005|publisher= Military & Aerospace Electronics magazine}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[High framerate video]]\n* [[Slow motion]]\n* [[Photron]] (Photron's FASTCAM High-speed Cameras)\n* [[Vision Research Phantom]] (Vision Research's Phantom High-Speed Cameras)\n* [[Mikrotron-GmbH|Mikrotron (high-speed cameras)]]\n* [[High-speed photography]]\n* [[Rapatronic camera]]\n* [[Burst mode (photography)]]\n* [[Hubert Schardin]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|High speed cameras}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:High-Speed Camera}}\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Cameras by type]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Slow motion]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|High-speed photography#High-speed film cameras}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\nA '''high-speed camera''' is a device capable of capturing moving images with exposures of less than 1/1,000 second or frame rates in excess of 250 frames per second.<ref>Journal of the Society of Motion Picture Engineers: High-Speed Photography, Preface p.5, Mar 1949</ref> It is used for recording fast-moving objects as photographic images onto a storage medium.  After recording, the images stored on the medium can be played back in [[slow motion]]. Early high-speed cameras used film to record the high-speed events, but were superseded by entirely electronic devices using either a [[charge-coupled device]] (CCD) or a [[CMOS]] [[active pixel sensor]], recording, typically, over 1,000 frames per second onto [[DRAM]], to be played back slowly to study the motion for scientific study of transient phenomena.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/HSV%20White%20Paper.pdf |title=High Frame Rate Electronic Imaging |access-date=2010-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000301/http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/HSV%20White%20Paper.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nA high-speed camera can be classified as:\n# A high-speed film camera which records to film,\n# A high-speed video camera which records to electronic memory,\n# A high-speed framing camera which records images on multiple image planes or multiple locations on the same image plane<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aimed-research.com/help.html | title=High-Speed Camera Tutorials}}</ref> (generally film or a network of CCD cameras),\n# A high-speed streak camera which records a series of line-sized images to film or electronic memory.\n\nA normal [[Film|motion picture]] film is played back at 24 [[frames per second]], while television uses 25 frames/s ([[PAL]]) or 29.97 frames/s ([[NTSC]]). High-speed film cameras can film up to a quarter of a million frames per second by running the film over a rotating [[prism (optics)|prism]] or [[mirror]] instead of using a [[shutter (photography)|shutter]], thus reducing the need for stopping and starting the film behind a shutter which would tear the film stock at such speeds. Using this technique one second of action can be stretched to more than ten minutes of playback time (super slow motion). High-speed video cameras are widely used for scientific research,<ref>scientific research {{Cite journal|last= Chen|first= Xianfeng |title= Effect of CH4\u2013Air Ratios on Gas Explosion Flame Microstructurec and Propagation Behaviors |journal= Energies |volume= 5 |issue= 10 |pages= 4132\u20134146 |doi= 10.3390/en5104132 |year= 2012 }}</ref><ref>scientific research{{cite web|last=Anderson|first= Christopher V. |title= Ballistic tongue projection in chameleons maintains high performance at low temperature|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/107/12/5495.full.pdf|accessdate=2 February 2010|publisher= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America}}</ref>  military test and evaluation,<ref>{{cite web|last=Chu|first= Dr. Peter C.|title= Non-Cylindrical Mine Drop Experiment |url= http://faculty.nps.edu/pcchu/web_paper/proceedings/jcot/midex2.pdf |date=4 May 2006|publisher= Seventh International Symposium on Technology and Mine Problem, NPS, Monterey, California, USA }}</ref> and industry.<ref>{{cite web|title= Photron Camera Honored by Japan Society of Mechanical Engineers |url= http://www.qualitymag.com/Articles/Industry_Headlines/BNP_GUID_9-5-2006_A_10000000000000241598|accessdate=January 23, 2008 |publisher=Quality Magazine}}</ref>  Examples of industrial applications are filming a manufacturing line to better tune the machine, or in the car industry filming a [[crash test]] to investigate the effect on the [[crash dummy]] passengers and the [[automobile]]. Today, the digital high-speed camera has replaced the film camera used for Vehicle Impact Testing.<ref>[http://www.motionvideoproducts.com/MVP%20papers/Kodak%20RO_SPIE.pdf Replacing 16&nbsp;mm Film Cameras with High Definition Digital Cameras]</ref> \n[[File:Schlieren Video Of Shotshell Transitional Intermediate Ballistics - Nathan Boor of Aimed Research.ogv|thumb|[[Schlieren]] video of an intermediate ballistic event of a shotshell cartridge. Nathan Boor, Aimed Research.]]\n[[Television series]] such as ''[[MythBusters]]'' and ''[[Time Warp (TV series)|Time Warp]]'' often use high-speed cameras to show their tests in slow motion. Saving the recorded high-speed images can be time consuming because {{As of|2017|lc=on}}, consumer cameras have resolutions up to four megapixels with frame rates of over 1,000 per second which will record at a rate of 11 gigabytes per second. Technologically these cameras are very advanced, yet saving images requires use of slower standard video-computer interfaces.<ref>[http://www.definitionmagazine.com/journal/2011/1/4/review-high-speed-cameras.html REVIEW: High Speed Cameras, Jan. 4, 2011]</ref> While recording is very fast, saving images is considerably slower.\nTo reduce the storage space required and the time required for people to examine a recording, only the parts of an action which are of interest or relevance can be selected to film. When recording a cyclical process for industrial breakdown analysis, only the relevant part of each cycle is filmed.\n\nA problem for high-speed cameras is the needed [[exposure (photography)|exposure]] for the film; very bright light is needed to be able to film at 40,000&nbsp;fps, sometimes leading to the subject of examination being destroyed because of the heat of the lighting.\nMonochromatic (black and white) filming is sometimes used to reduce the light intensity required.\nEven higher speed imaging is possible using specialized electronic [[charge-coupled device]] (CCD) imaging systems, which can achieve speeds of over 25&nbsp;million fps. These cameras, however, still use rotating mirrors, like their older film counterparts. Solid state cameras can achieve speeds of up to 10 million fps. <ref>https://www.shimadzu.com/an/test/hpv/hpv-x2/index.html</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228937545_Brandaris_128_A_digital_25_million_fra