tered around the use of high-speed cameras to slow things down that are usually too fast to see with the naked eye.\n*High-speed cameras are frequently used in [[television production]]s of many major sporting events for [[slow motion]] [[instant replay]]s when normal slow motion is not slow enough, such as international [[Cricket]] matches.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nacinc.com/did-you-know/nac-cameras-are-popular-choices-for-european-broadcasting/| title=NAC High Speed Cameras Are Popular Choices for European Broadcasting| accessdate = 8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Uses in science==\nHigh-speed cameras are frequently used in science in order to characterize events which happen too fast for traditional film speeds. [[Biomechanics]] employs such cameras to capture high-speed animal movements, such as [[jumping]] by frogs and insects,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kesel |first= Antonia B.|title= Quantifying the Landing Reaction of Cockroaches |url= http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/doc/ARI/ARI%20Study%20Report/ACT-RPT-BIO-ARI-08-6302-CockroachLanding-Bremen.pdf |accessdate=15 December 2009|journal=University of Applied Sciences Bremen}}</ref> [[Aquatic predation#Suction feeding|suction feeding]] in fish, the strikes of [[mantis shrimp]], and the aerodynamic study of pigeons' helicopter-like movements <ref>{{cite journal | last=Ros | first=Ivo G. | last2=Bassman | first2=Lori C. | last3=Badger | first3=Marc A. | last4=Pierson | first4=Alyssa N. | last5=Biewener | first5=Andrew A. | title=Pigeons steer like helicopters and generate down- and upstroke lift during low speed turns | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume=108 | issue=50 | date=2011-12-13 | issn=0027-8424 | pmid=22123982 | pmc=3250151 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1107519108 | pages=19990\u201319995 | bibcode=2011PNAS..10819990R }}</ref> using [[motion analysis]] of the resulting sequences from one or more cameras to characterize the motion in either 2-D or 3-D.\n\nThe move from film to digital technology has greatly reduced the difficulty in use of these technologies with unpredictable behaviors, specifically via the use of continuous recording and post-triggering. With film high-speed cameras, an investigator must start the film then attempt to entice the animal to perform the behavior in the short time before the film runs out, resulting in many useless sequences where the animal behaves too late or not at all. In modern digital high-speed cameras,<ref>{{Cite book|last= Balch|first= Kris S.| title= Fourth-generation motion analyzer |url=http://proceedings.spiedigitallibrary.org/proceeding.aspx?articleid=950818 |date=16 September 1990|journal=Proc. SPIE 1358, 19th Intl Congress on High-Speed Photography and Photonics|volume= 1358|pages= 373\u2013398|doi= 10.1117/12.23937|isbn= 9780819404190}}</ref> the camera can simply record continuously as the investigator attempts to elicit the behavior, following which a trigger button will stop the recording and allow the investigator to save a given time interval before and after the trigger (determined by frame rate, image size and memory capacity during continuous recording). Most software allows saving a subset of recorded frames, minimizing file size issues by eliminating useless frames before or after the sequence of interest. Such triggering can also be used to synchronize recording across multiple cameras.\n\nThe explosion of alkali metals on contact with water has been studied using a high-speed camera. Frame-by-frame analysis of a sodium/potassium alloy exploding in water, combined with molecular dynamic simulations, suggested that the initial expansion may be the result of a [[Coulomb explosion]] and not combustion of hydrogen gas as previously thought.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mason|first=Philip E.|last2=Uhlig|first2=Frank|last3=Van\u011bk|first3=V\u00e1clav|last4=Buttersack|first4=Tillmann|last5=Bauerecker|first5=Sigurd|last6=Jungwirth|first6=Pavel|date=2015-03-01|title=Coulomb explosion during the early stages of the reaction of alkali metals with water|journal=Nature Chemistry|language=en|volume=7|issue=3|pages=250\u2013254|doi=10.1038/nchem.2161|pmid=25698335|issn=1755-4330|bibcode=2015NatCh...7..250M}}</ref>\n\nDigital high-speed camera footage has strongly contributed to the understanding of [[lightning]] when combined with [[electric field]] measuring instrumentation and sensors which can map the propagation of lightning leaders through the detection of [[radio waves]] generated by this process.<ref name=ztresearch>{{cite web |url=https://ztresearch.blog/education/ |website=ZT Research |access-date=8 September 2018|title=Education |date=2017-05-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses in industry==\nWhen moving from reactive maintenance to [[predictive maintenance]], it is crucial that breakdowns are really understood. One of the basic analysis techniques is to use high-speed cameras in order to characterize events which happen too fast to see, e.g. during production. Similar to use in science, with a pre- or post-triggering capability the camera can simply record continuously as the mechanic waits for the breakdown to happen, following which a trigger signal (internal or external) will stop the recording and allow the investigator to save a given time interval prior to the trigger (determined by frame rate, image size, and memory capacity during continuous recording). Some software allows viewing the issues in real time, by displaying only a subset of recorded frames, minimizing file size and watch time issues by eliminating useless frames before or after the sequence of interest.\n\nHigh-speed video cameras are used to augment other industrial technologies such as x-ray radiography.  When used with the proper phosphor screen which converts x-rays into visible light, high-speed cameras can be used to capture high-speed x-ray videos of events inside mechanical devices and biological specimens. The imaging speed is mainly limited by the phosphor screen decay rate and intensity gain which has a direct relationship on the camera's exposure. Pulsed x-ray sources limit frame rate and should be properly synchronized with camera frame captures.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aimed-research.com/Services.html | title=High-Speed Imaging Services - Aimed Research}}</ref>\n\n==Uses in warfare==\nIn 1950 [[Morton Sultanoff]], an engineer for the U.S.&nbsp;Army at Aberdeen Proving ground, invented a super high-speed camera that took frames at one-millionth of a second, and was fast enough to record the shock wave of a small explosion.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ydgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA158&dq=1954+Popular+Mechanics+January&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WSfYT4GmKcOA2wW3ycWOCw&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBzgy#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Super Speed Camera Films Shock Wave\"] ''Popular Mechanics'', October 1950, p. 158.</ref> High Speed digital cameras have been used to study how mines dropped from the air will deploy in near-shore regions,<ref>weapon development{{cite web |last= Chu |first= Dr. Peter C. |title= Non-Cylindrical Mine Drop Experiment |url= http://faculty.nps.edu/pcchu/web_paper/proceedings/jcot/midex2.pdf |accessdate= 4 May 2006 |publisher= Seventh International Symposium on Technology and Mine Problem, NPS, Monterey, California, USA }}.  By using high speed digital cameras to record and playback the images in slow motion, the trajectory of a mine entering into the water can be optimized for accuracy by adjusting the shape of the mine and the entry angle into the water.  There are many instances of high speed digital cameras used to study firearm ballistics{{cite web|title=Handgun Wounding Effects Due to Bullet Rotational Velocity|url=http://www.brassfetcher.com/Wounding%20Theory/Handgun%20Wounding%20Effects%20due%20to%20Rotational%20Velocity.pdf|accessdate=18 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222013624/http://www.brassfetcher.com/Wounding%20Theory/Handgun%20Wounding%20Effects%20due%20to%20Rotational%20Velocity.pdf|archive-date=22 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> including development of various weapon systems.  In 2005 high speed digital cameras with 4 megapixel resolution, recording at 1500 fps, were replacing the 35mm and 70mm high speed film cameras used on tracking mounts on test ranges that capture ballistic intercepts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bridges |first= Andrew |title= INDUSTRY VIEW: Military test ranges make the switch from film to digital imaging |url=http://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/print/volume-16/issue-8/departments/electro-optics-watch/industry-view-military-test-ranges-make-the-switch-from-film-to-digital-imaging.html|date=1 August 2005|accessdate= 1 August 2005|publisher= Military & Aerospace Electronics magazine}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[High framerate video]]\n* [[Slow motion]]\n* [[Photron]] (Photron's FASTCAM High-speed Cameras)\n* [[Vision Research Phantom]] (Vision Research's Phantom High-Speed Cameras)\n* [[Mikrotron-GmbH|Mikrotron (high-speed cameras)]]\n* [[High-speed photography]]\n* [[Rapatronic camera]]\n* [[Burst mode (photography)]]\n* [[Hubert Schardin]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|High speed cameras}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:High-Speed Camera}}\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Cameras by type]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Slow motion]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-speed_camera"}
